[5] Democratic Republic of the Congo (Kinshasa)
Date: Wed 25 Mar 2020
Source: Ministry of Health Bulletin [in French, machine and Mod.MPP trans., edited]
https://mailchi.mp/ebd208ec3cee/covid-19-bulletin-n1-du-24-mars-3897569?e=e838b4d57b


[A daily newsletter was produced by the Ministry of Health of the Democratic Republic of the Congo during the ebolavirus outbreak. Now that transmission of the ebolavirus has been interrupted (waiting for 2 incubation periods for announcement), the Ministry has been issuing the same platform bulletin daily in response to the COVID-19 outbreak.- Mod.MPP]

Welcome to this new daily bulletin on the evolution of the coronavirus pandemic (COVID-19) in the Democratic Republic of Congo. This bulletin presents daily official and authorized information on the entire situation of the Covid-19 in the DRC.

Epidemiological evolution of COVID-19 in the Democratic Republic of the Congo

- Since the start of the epidemic declared on [10 Mar 2020], the cumulative total is 51 confirmed cases. In total, there were 3 deaths, including:
- 3 new confirmed cases;
- no new deaths from confirmed cases;
- pending approval by the competent services, the number of people cured will be given in the next bulletins.

News

- The President of the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Head of State, Felix-Antoine Tshisekedi Tshilombo, announced Tuesday [24 Mar 2020] on the National Radio and Television, in his message to the nation, additional measures for the implementation of its previous decisions to contain COVID-19 in the DRC.

- Among the decisions taken, the President of the Republic, in view of the seriousness and dangerous nature of the current health situation, declared a state of health emergency in the DRC.

- "We must all arm ourselves with a solid spirit of resignation and give up all activities incompatible with the measures and the recommendations of the Government which must on no occasion be ruined," said the Head of State, specifying that the 1sr decisions taken were not" sufficiently followed by the population."

- This is how he decided to reinforce the measures announced on [18 Mar 2020] by prohibiting, among other things, movements between Kinshasa, the focus of the pandemic, and the provinces and vice versa. This decision cancels all migratory movements by air, land, and river.

- He also decided to close all of the country's borders, except for humanitarian convoys, especially food and medicine. Barriers will be erected to subject all crews to "rigorous departure and arrival control" in terms of COVID-19.

- He instructed the political and administrative authorities in Kinshasa to prohibit all gatherings and to install hand-washing points throughout the city, as well as to support the specialized services of N'djili airport "so that no one 'escapes hygiene control'.

- The Head of State Felix-Antoine Tshisekedi, calling for the unity of the nation, announced the imminent establishment of a National Solidarity Fund against the coronavirus. He reassured that the Task Force which he chairs reflects, "without delay on the advisability of using tablets and injectables of hydroxy chloroquine, an approach likely to stem the coronavirus."

For access to Congolese territory
---------------------------------
1. Suspension, until further notice, from 20 Mar 2020, all flights from countries at risk and transit countries. Only airplanes and cargo ships and other means of freight transport will be authorized to enter the national territory and their personnel subject to controls.
2. Postponement of trips to the Democratic Republic of the Congo of all passengers residing in countries at risk until further notice.
3. Requirement for all passengers, upon arrival at national borders, to complete an information sheet and to submit, without exception, to the obligation to wash their hands and take their temperature.
4. Imposition of a quarantine of 14 days maximum on any person suspected at the end of the temperature test, a thorough examination, and if necessary to intern in the hospitals provided for this purpose, the people who would test positive.
5. Provision of all maritime, river, lake, and land entry points in the national territory with the same surveillance system to strengthen the control of passengers from abroad.
6. Systematically subjecting people leaving Kinshasa to the various provinces of the DRC to control measures in order to avoid the spread of this pandemic to the rest of our country.

For gatherings of people
------------------------
1. Prohibition of all gatherings, meetings, celebrations, of more than 20 people in public places outside the family home.
2. Closure of schools, universities, official, and private higher institutes throughout the national territory from [19 Mar 2020] for a period of 4 weeks.
3. Suspension of all services for a period of 4 weeks from [19 Mar 2020].
4. Suspension of sports activities in stadiums and other places of sports gathering until further notice.
5. Prohibition, until further notice, of the opening of discos, bars, cafes, terraces, and restaurants.
6. Ban on the organization of mourning in rooms and homes. The remains will be taken directly from the morgue to the place of burial and in a limited number of accompanying persons.
7. Management at government expense of all cases tested positive throughout the country.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Many of the steps outlined in the report above are the same as what the DRC implements when they are dealing with an ebolavirus outbreak. A major challenge will be implementing these steps in Kinshasa, with an estimated population in 2018 of 13.2 million inhabitants (https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/EN.URB.LCTY?locations=CD).

What is interesting is that given a recognition of water access difficulties, hand washing stations will be set up around the city to permit frequent hand washing.

Note that the Hopkins CSSE data and the Worldometer data show 45 and 48 cases reported from Congo DR as of midnight 26 Mar 2020, whereas the official government tally as of 24 Mar 2020 is 51. - Mod.MPP

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of DR Congo: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7143838,194]

